[size=6][b]Supply Needs Planner[/b][/size]

Right-click a station (or its build storage) with selected trader ships and have them queue [b]Execute Trade[/b] deals that fulfill that target's needs - buying the wares from your own stations (or any non-hostile station) and delivering them.

The orders are ordinary [b]Execute Trade[/b] deals - the same kind a station trader makes. What counts as the target's "needs" depends on whose target it is:

[list]
[*]For [b]your own[/b] station or build storage, the needs come from its per-ware [b]storage targets[/b] - how much of each ware it wants minus how much it already holds. This works even at a zero account - through virtual offers.[/*]
[*]For an [b]allied / NPC[/b] target, the needs are the real buy offers it is already advertising - cross-faction delivery can only go through real offers.[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]Why[/b][/size]

Sometimes a freshly planned station just sits there waiting - in a forgotten corner of the universe or right amid the densest traffic lanes - while dozens of trader ships stream past hauling wares from A to B, never to it. Most stations do get built eventually (some trader decides to visit), but it is not a rare situation either: a station can wait a very long time for even the first module's wares.

And until that first module stands, the game will not let you assign a manager. No manager means no subordinates, which means no [font=Courier New]Trade for Build Storage[/font] ships. From there your options are: 1 - wait, 2 - forget, 3 - start frantically clicking your own trader ships through manual trades - first removing whatever orders they already had (harmful in itself), then looping "buy ware - set quantity - confirm, sell ware - set quantity - confirm", six clicks per order.

This mod is option 4: one right-click on the [b]station itself[/b] (it resolves the build storage for you, so it works before the first module is up), one config window, one [b]Run planner[/b]. The screenshot run queued 100 trade orders for 5 ships - 600 clicks saved.

Use cases:

[list]
[*]Kickstart a freshly planned station's build.[/*]
[*]Fill a station's build storage completely.[/*]
[*]Top up a shipyard with a targeted caravan run.[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]Game version compatibility[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][i] 9.00 release[/i] - [b]supported[/b][/*]
[*][i] 9.00 betas and release candidates[/i] - [b]supported[/b][/*]
[*][i] 8.00 release[/i] - [b]supported[/b][/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]Dependencies[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]SirNukes Mod Support APIs[/b] ([url=https://www.nexusmods.com/x4foundations/mods/503]link[/url]) - hard dependency. Provides the Lua loader, Interact Menu API and Simple Menu API.[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]Usage[/b][/size]

[list=1]
[*]Select one or more cargo/trader ships.[/*]
[*]Right-click any non-hostile station (your own, or friendly/neutral NPC).[/*]
[*]Choose [b]Fulfill station needs[/b] or [b]Fulfill build storage needs[/b] (the build-storage entry only appears when the station has a build storage).[/*]
[*]Tune the config and click [b]Run planner[/b].[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]How it plans[/b][/size]

Clicking [b]Run planner[/b] plans every round trip in one pass and writes all the resulting buy/sell orders straight into the ships' queues. Each ship gets one or more round trips: a trip loads from source stations up to the [i]round-trip fill target[/i], then delivers the lot to the target in a single drop. When a trip finishes the ship rolls into the next queued one, and keeps going until the target's needs are covered (or you cancel the orders). The selected ships share the work, so the same stock is never booked twice.

If selected ships already carry cargo, the planner can either leave it alone, sell it first, or drop it before the ship's first planned trip. In sell-first mode it first tries to deliver matching cargo to the planner target itself; if the target cannot take all of it, the rest is sold to the closest reachable buyer. This can turn a half-loaded trader from "not enough free cargo space" into useful first delivery instead of wasted routing.

The planner can also keep or flush a participating ship's existing order queue. Flushing only happens for ships that actually receive planner orders; unused selected ships are left alone.

Each trip is [b]spread across wares[/b] rather than filling up on one. A station is built module by module and every module needs a little of each resource, so a trip first gives every needed ware a fair slice (up to [i]Max wares per trip[/i]), then tops the cargo up toward the fill target. The result is that the target starts receiving a bit of everything from the very first trip instead of waiting several trips for the last ware to show up. When there are more needed wares than [i]Max wares per trip[/i], the wares that lead each trip rotate so none is starved - raising [i]Max wares per trip[/i] and [i]Max trades per trip[/i] lets a single trip carry more variety. Multiple selected ships divide the wares between them, so the first round of trips fans out across distinct wares: e.g. 3 ships with [i]Max wares per trip[/i] = 2 can cover 6 different needs in the very first round.

Within a trip the ship buys [b]farthest source first[/b] and the source nearest the target last, so the loaded final hop to the delivery point is as short as possible.

[size=4][b]Config[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Source restriction[/b] - [font=Courier New]Only own stations[/font], [font=Courier New]Own stations first[/font], or [font=Courier New]No restrictions[/font] (any known, non-hostile station).[/*]
[*][b]Source priority[/b] - Pick the [font=Courier New]Cheapest[/font] source first, or the [font=Courier New]Nearest[/font] to the target.[/*]
[*][b]Transaction handling[/b] - [i](own targets only)[/i] How the delivery leg is settled - see below.[/*]
[*][b]Pre-existing ship cargo[/b] - What to do with cargo already aboard selected ships - see below.[/*]
[*][b]Pre-existing ship orders[/b] - Keep existing orders, or flush them before adding planner orders for ships that actually participate.[/*]
[*][b]Max source distance[/b] - Ignore sources more than this many gate jumps from the target.[/*]
[*][b]Max price above average[/b] - Skip a source priced more than this % over the ware's average price (500 = effectively no cap).[/*]
[*][b]Fulfill percentage[/b] - Cap each need at this share of the target's current demand.[/*]
[*][b]Max wares per trip[/b] - Distinct wares a ship loads on one round trip.[/*]
[*][b]Max trades per trip[/b] - Total source pickups (buy legs) on one round trip.[/*]
[*][b]Max round trips per ship[/b] - Cap how many round trips a single ship is queued.[/*]
[*][b]Round-trip fill target[/b] - Close a trip once it reaches this % of cargo (0 = fill to capacity).[/*]
[*][b]Minimum cargo usage per trip[/b] - Discard an attempted trip below this % full - keeps ships from making near-empty runs. [b]Setting this too high can leave small remainders unfulfilled.[/b][/*]
[*][b]Minimum per-trade fill[/b] - Reject any single buy leg smaller than this % of cargo - avoids trivial pickups. [b]Setting this too high can skip valid small trades.[/b][/*]
[/list]

The planner window opens with the previous run config if one exists; otherwise it starts from defaults. [b]Restore default config[/b] and [b]Use previous config[/b] remain available in the menu, so you can compare or undo edits before running. "Use previous" is greyed out until a run has saved one.

The [b]Select wares to fulfill[/b] button opens a sub-menu with one checkbox per needed ware, so you can drop individual wares from a run. It also has a handful of quick-select helper buttons ([i]all[/i], [i]real offers only[/i], [i]pure / intermediate / primary / supply resources only[/i]) - convenient on a wharf with a long ware list, though for most station builds the full default selection is what you want anyway. Manual testing shown that most of the time it's effectively same "select all" and "deselect all" buttons with a bit more fancy labels.

[size=3][b]Transaction handling[/b][/size]

For your [b]own[/b] station or build storage you can choose how the delivery leg is settled. (Allied / NPC targets never show this choice - they can only be supplied through their real buy offers, so the planner always uses real trade for them.)

[list]
[*][b]Real offers[/b] - Delivers against the target's real, priced buy offers - the classic behaviour. Needs the station to have an account and be advertising the offers.[/*]
[*][b]Virtual offers (overrides check)[/b] - Synthesizes a zero-price, virtual-money buy offer for each short ware, capped to the ware's existing offer amount where one is set - so it respects any logistics overrides you've configured. No account needed.[/*]
[*][b]Virtual offers (by ware capacity)[/b] - Same synthesized offers, but sized straight from per-ware storage capacity ([font=Courier New]target - current[/font]), ignoring any advertised desired amount.[/*]
[/list]

[b]Why a virtual offer instead of a "transfer wares" \ "exchange wares" order?[/b] The [font=Courier New]virtualmoney[/font] flag is exactly what vanilla itself uses when mining ships sell to a commander's build station, so the delivery stays an ordinary [b]Execute Trade[/b] the game already understands. The only alternative - the [i]Exchange Wares[/i] order - isn't reachable from Mission Director script and would have to be reimplemented in Lua, buying nothing but a lot of pain and re-testing. So the original mod stays exactly as it was, and this simply adds one more case it can handle: supplying a station that has no account, or only a small one.

[size=3][b]Pre-existing cargo and orders[/b][/size]

Selected ships are not always empty. Existing cargo reduces usable free space, which can make a ship fail the [b]Minimum cargo usage[/b] gate and receive no planner orders. The planner offers three cargo modes:

[list]
[*][b]Keep (plan around it)[/b] - Default. Existing cargo stays aboard and only free cargo space is used for planning.[/*]
[*][b]Sell to closest buyer first[/b] - Before the ship's first planner trip, sell existing cargo. Matching cargo is offered to the planner target first, then any remainder goes to the closest reachable buyer. Cargo with no buyer stays aboard.[/*]
[*][b]Drop cargo (jettison)[/b] - Before the ship's first planner trip, drop existing cargo as lootable crates. This is destructive, so it is never the default.[/*]
[/list]

The separate [b]Pre-existing ship orders[/b] setting controls the selected ships' current order queues:

[list]
[*][b]Keep[/b] - Default. Planner orders are appended after whatever the ship already had queued.[/*]
[*][b]Flush[/b] - Cancel the ship's existing AI orders before adding planner orders. This is only done for ships that actually receive planner orders.[/*]
[/list]

If ships are skipped while cargo mode is [b]Keep[/b], the planner may show a hint that existing cargo left too little free space. If ships hit [b]Max trades per trip[/b] before filling up, another hint shows how many ships hit that limit.

[size=3][b]Tuning note: priority, sources and the cargo floor[/b][/size]

These settings interact. In X4 a station's price for a ware rises as its stock falls, so the [b]cheapest[/b] sources are usually the ones holding the [b]most[/b] stock - which also means bigger pickups per stop. Your [b]own[/b] stations tend to sit on large stockpiles too. [b]Nearest[/b] sources, especially under [b]No restrictions[/b], are often small nearby NPC factories: pricier, and only a few units each, so a trip has to make many small pickups to fill up.

The practical consequence: a high [b]Minimum cargo usage[/b] is hard to reach with [font=Courier New]No restrictions[/font] + [font=Courier New]Nearest[/font], because the small fragmented pickups run into the [b]Max trades per trip[/b] limit before the ship is full, and the under-filled trip is discarded - so some wares (the ones with only tiny nearby sellers) may never get delivered. In testing, floors much above ~40% started leaving wares unfilled on that combination.

To soften this, [b]Nearest[/b] already self-corrects: whenever a nearest-sourced trip can't reach the cargo floor, it retries that same basket once with the sources re-ordered by biggest stock first - larger legs from deeper stockpiles, which usually clears the floor at the cost of a slightly longer route. It's a rescue, not a guarantee, so if you still see the "hit the Max trades limit" notice or wares going undelivered: lower [b]Minimum cargo usage[/b], raise [b]Max trades per trip[/b], or switch priority to [b]Cheapest[/b] (and/or [b]Own stations first[/b]) to pull from bigger, deeper stockpiles from the start.

